<TITLE> ACC gets court approval to quiz Hasina </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Oct 23 (bdnews24.com)  A Dhaka court Tuesday allowed an investigator to quiz former prime minister Sheikh Hasina on charges of taking Tk 3 crore in bribe for shady approval for three barge-mounted power plants in Haripur, Shikal Baha and Khulna. The Anticorruption Commission will question the Awami League president in connection with the graft case filed against a total of seven people on Sept 2. Judge Md Mizanur Rahman of the Chief Metropolitan Magistrate's Court allowed investigating officer and ACC deputy director Morshed Alam to interrogate the former prime minister who has been detained in special jail since July 16. In his petition on Monday, Alam said the former premier needs to be quizzed by an anticorruption taskforce for the sake of a proper investigation. According to case details, Hasinawhen she was prime ministerapproved the appointment of Summit Group and United Group for setting up three barge-mounted power plants, depriving lowest bidder New England Power Company Consortium of the job. In exchange, Hasina took Tk 3 crore in bribe from Summit and United Groups, which was spent to buy a piece of land, including a two-storey building at Dhanmondi Road No. 32, to build Bangabandhu Memorial Trust. ACC deputy director MM Shabbir Hasan filed the corruption case with Tejgaon Police Station on Sept 2 against seven people, including Hasina. Other accused are former power and energy secretary Towfique-e-Elahi Chowdhury, former chairman of the Power Development Board Nooruddin Mahmud Kamal, managing director of Summit Industries and Mercantile Corporation Ltd Muhammad Aziz Khan, director of the same company Muhammad Farid Khan, United Group chairman Hasan Mahmud Raja and director Abul Kalam Azad. bdnew
